 The VDC is composed of two wire planes with 0.335 m vertical separation,
 each plane contains 368 sense wires 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fissum2001108"

\end_inset

.
 Each plane is selected a perpendicular UV wires configuration, which are
 inclined angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 respect to the dispersive and non-dispersive directions.
 The chambers are filled with the gas mixture of argon and ethane.
 The electric field is generated by a high voltage with the nominal operating
 voltage of -4 kV.
 Each wire is connected to the Time-to-Digital Converter (TDC) to reconstruct
 the track.
 The timing is used to determine the drift distances for each wire.
 A linear fit of drift distances versus wire position is used to determine
 the cross-over point of the track.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The VDC's track efficiency is defined as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jiemultitrack"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Eff_{VDC}=\frac{N_{good}}{N_{total}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{total}$
\end_inset

 is the total events, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{good}$
\end_inset

 is the number of good events which have at least one track reconstructed
 in VDC and verified by the lead glass calorimeters.
 Usually we use the single-track efficiency instead:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Eff_{VDC\_single}=\frac{N_{single}}{N_{total}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{single}$
\end_inset

 is the number of events which only have one good track.
